🧠 Why Can You Call puts Anywhere?

You answered:

Because everything inherits from Object.

That’s partly correct.

But here’s the full chain:

BasicObject
   ↑
Object
   ↑
YourClass

Now important part:

👉 Kernel is included inside Object.

Meaning internally Ruby does something like:

class Object
  include Kernel
end

So when your class inherits from Object,
it also gets all methods from Kernel.

And guess where puts is defined?

👉 Inside Kernel.

That’s why you can write:

puts "Hello"

Even inside any class.

🔥 So The Real Reason

You can call puts anywhere because:

Your class inherits from Object

Object includes Kernel

Kernel defines puts

So Ruby finds puts in the lookup chain

🧠 Even More Precise Answer (Interview Level)

If interviewer asks:

“Why can you call puts without defining it?”

You say:

Because puts is defined in the Kernel module, which is included in Object. Since all classes inherit from Object by default, Kernel methods are available everywhere.

That answer is strong and precise.

